<comment datatype='string'>The basal level of &lt;i&gt;rsd&lt;/i&gt; transcription is maintained by using the downstream rsdp2 promoter recognized by E&amp;sigma;&lt;sup&gt;70&lt;/sup&gt;. On the basis of sequence similarity and unique expression patterns, such as the inverse relationship with the growth rate, the rsdp2 promoter can be classified as a member of the gearbox family of promoters, but it cannot be transcribed by E&amp;sigma;&lt;sup&gt;38&lt;/sup&gt; &lt;i&gt;in vivo&lt;/i&gt; or &lt;i&gt;in vitro&lt;/i&gt;. Under certain circumstances, the upstream sequence including the rsdp1 promoter exerts an inhibitory effect on the rsdp2 function, because the deletion of the rsdp1 region results in an increase in transcription from the downstream rsdp2 promoter. The mechanism of inhibition by the upstream sequence remains unsolved.</comment>
